time in decades agricultural commodity markets could experience a sustained increase in prices breaking the long term price decline that has benefited food consumers worldwide whether this transition occurs and how it will affect global hunger and poverty remain to be seen will food markets begin to track the volatile energy market in terms of price and availability will changes in agricultural commodity markets benefit net food producers and raise farm incomes in poor countries how will biofuels induced changes in agricultural commodity markets affect net consumers of food at risk are over 800 million food insecure people mostly in rural areas and dependant to some extent on agriculture for incomes who live on less than $1 per day and spend the majority of their incomes on food an additional 2 to 2.5 billion people living on $1 to $2 per day are also at risk as rising commodity prices could pull them swiftly into a food insecure state download html+ go to site external http www environmentmagazine org parent research biofuels expansion implications for global food markets land use change and climate food and nutrition security in an era of economic volatility topics biofuels energy food security global hunger sustainable development search fse search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages publication news gates foundation gives $3.8 million to stanford university for biofuels food security research december 1 2007 fsi stanford fse news publications of interest program on food security and the environment information brochure fse stanford university 2007 pdf+ cover center on food security and the environment 2011 12 brochure center on food security and the environment 2011 pdf+ cover support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 4920 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
